-- Crude Options Volatility Falls as Futures Advance for Sixth Day
-- B y   E l i o t   C a r o o m
-- 2013-08-16T20:28:22Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-08-16/crude-options-volatility-falls-as-futures-advance-for-sixth-day.html
Crude oil options volatility fell as
crude advanced for a sixth straight day.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
October was 21.34 percent on the  New York  Mercantile Exchange at
4:05 p.m., down from 21.76 percent yesterday.  West Texas Intermediate crude for October delivery gained
10 cents to settle at $107.29 a barrel on the Nymex. The front-month September futures rose 13 cents to $107.46.  The most active options in electronic trading today were
January $70 puts, which fell 2 cents to 9 cents on volume of
3,533 lots as of 4:08 p.m. October $100 puts were second-most
active, declining 9 cents to 56 cents on 2,618 contracts.  Puts made up 53 percent of electronic trading volume. In
the prior session, bearish bets accounted for 54 percent of the
93,463 contracts exchanged.  January $87.50 puts were the most-active options yesterday
with 6,000 lots exchanging hands as they fell 7 cents to $1.02 a
barrel. December $95 puts fell 7 cents to $1.54 on volume of
3,517 contracts.  Open interest was highest for December $80 puts, with
39,654 contracts. Next were December $90 puts with 36,914 lots
and December $105 calls with 35,313.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information the next business day on open-outcry volume, where the bulk of options activity occurs.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Eliot Caroom in New York at 
 ecaroom@bloomberg.net  